# Black History Month
## Here's a summary of the article about Black History Month:

Black History Month, starting on Saturday, celebrates Black people and their experiences. The celebration's origins trace back to Carter G. Woodson, who founded the Association for the Study of African American Life and History (ASALH) in 1915. Woodson initiated Negro History Week in February 1926, which later evolved into Black History Month in the United States.

Woodson, born to enslaved parents, was the second African American to receive a PhD from Harvard. He chose the second week of February for Negro History Week due to its association with Abraham Lincoln's and Frederick Douglass' (Douglass Day) birthdays.

Students from Black and white colleges pushed to extend Negro History Week, leading to the first observance of Black History Month at Kent State University in 1970. President Gerald R. Ford officially recognized it in 1976, with President Ronald Reagan further acknowledging it in 1986.

Woodson's work aimed to counter the misrepresentation of Black history and to highlight the achievements and contributions of Black people. His efforts included developing educational materials and promoting the study of Black history in schools.

The article also highlights the story of Claudette Colvin, a civil rights activist who, inspired by her history education, refused to give up her bus seat to white passengers in 1955. Her act of defiance contributed to the civil rights movement.

[Woodson believed in emphasizing the role of Black people in history rather than just focusing on Black history itself.](https://archive.org/details/sim_black-history-bulletin_1950-03_13_6/page/122/mode/2up?view=theater)

